{{tone|date=November 2013}} {{Infobox person |name = Catalina |image = India Catalina Cartagena Colombia by Camilo Rueda Lopez.png |image_size = |alt = Statue of India Catalina in Cartagena de Indias. |caption = Statue of India Catalina in [[Cartagena de Indias]]. |birth_date = c. 1495 |death_date = unknown |other_names = |known_for = Translator for [[Pedro de Heredia]] during the [[Spanish conquest of the Chibchan Nations]]. |occupation = [[Translator]], [[interpreter]] |spouse = Alonso Montañez }}
'''India Catalina''' (c. 1495 – ?) was an [[Indigenous peoples in Colombia|indigenous]] woman (almost certainly [[Calamari people|Calamari]]) from the Colombian [[Atlantic]] coast, who accompanied [[Pedro de Heredia]] and played a role in the [[Spain|Spanish]] conquest of [[Colombia]], acting as interpreter and intermediary.
==History== Catalina was abducted in 1509 by Spanish conqueror [[Diego de Nicuesa]] from an indigenous settlement known as Zamba o Galerazamba, where she was the daughter of the local chief. She was sent to [[Santo Domingo]], where she learned the [[Spanish language]] and adopted the [[Catholic]] religion. Pedro de Heredia required her to serve as an interpreter to the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]]. Afterwards, she married [[Alonso Montanez|Alonso Montañez]], Pedro de Heredia's nephew.{{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}
The events of the Spanish conquest in the area of modern [[Cartagena, Colombia|Cartagena]] ended with the complete annihilation of the Calamari people, which happened while she was enslaved and abducted by the Spaniards.{{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}
The name of Catalina India appeared in a letter sent for Pedro de Heredia to [[Carlos V, Holy Roman Emperor|King Carlos V]] in 1533. No one knew what her real name was because he{{clarify|reason=Pedro? Diego?|date=December 2014}} began calling her 'Catalina' from 1509 when the Diego de Nicuesa expedition kidnapped and took her to Santo Domingo where was educated as a Spaniard. From that time she would use Spanish dress only but was still considered a slave.
When they returned to Cartagena twenty years after, she was changed.{{clarify|reason=this is not self-explanatory. She was double her original age, for one thing|date=December 2014}} She made the first contact with [[Corinche|Corinche Indians]] after her arrival with Heredia, on the 14 January 1533. She translated for Heredia in the pacification of the many Indian towns as [[turbaco]]s that he eliminated in combat to Juan de La Cosa many years ago.{{clarify|reason=last sentence very unclear|date=December 2014}}
==Monument== [[File:India02.jpg|200px|thumb|right|The monument is located in the historic center of Cartagena. St Felipe castle in the background]]
The monument to India Catalina was sculpted by [[Eladio Gil Zambrana]] and presented to the public in 1974. Small scale replicas are used in the [[Cartagena Film Festival]] awards.
